I don't think CSS is abstract enough. Most UI developers don't, which explains the existence of grid systems and "frameworks." These tools can do no more than answer the problem: In respecting the separation of concerns w/r/t the relationship between HTML and other layers of the UI, to what extent should abstractions be included in UI development practices and what should the language of those abstractions be; as the names of that language should constitute the conventions of those practices.

HTML is the language of the Web. In HTML documents, this markup language <em>describes</em>, in a largely typographical way, <em>content</em> while giving it <em>form</em>. The markup languages tells us that something is a paragraph or a header, an unordered list or a data table. These formats are historically grounded in print production, typesetting, typography, desktop publishing, what is proverbially known as <em>print. </em>In <em>authoring </em>an HTML document, a web developer is not herself <em>the author </em>of what is being said, but rather <em>an author of how to say it in the context of the Web.</em> In much the same way  that <em>House Style </em>rules at the end of the day, thus enabling the rapid production of content, HTML is <em>the House Style of the Web.</em> UI Developers, HTML coders, frontend engineers, etc. are thus <em>authors of the Web.</em>

Of course upon first impression one may notice that the vocabulary of HTML is fairly small, yet we should not assume that HTML itself it is "limited." The derivation and affinity of its syntax to SGML and XML support its robustness and range of application (metadata, DOM, microformats, XSLT, etc.). These concerns aside, the "language of the Web" says little about the typographical elements and attributes which come from HTML but rather the more obscurely known DIV, SPAN, @class, @id, and others: tags and elements <em>that lack inherent meaning</em>. From a typesetter's look, these entities play the necessary analogous role of enabling one to conceptualize margins, gutters, space. CSS indeed gives us the ability to undertake typesetting, design and layout, but the notion of the meaningless entities partly defines the practice of developing CSS and JavaScript.

In HTML5 we see this class of entity, the meaningless entity, receive greater attention. The ARTICLE, FOOTER, ASIDE and others, we are to understand, behave much the same as the DIV.

<em> </em><em>HTML Descriptions</em> are computational and communal in nature; they are bridges between an manifest agreement in language within the social structure of human beings and an explicit standard implicitly adopted by computer systems. I say "adopted" for the fact that figurative qualities aside, crawlers, bots, scrubbers, spiders, and other algorithmically trained entities are, from a UI developer's look, each <em>readers</em>. What matters here is the <em>flow, </em>the flow of document content.

Form and flow in HTML are tricky since <em>form </em>is manifest under a multitude of interpretations; e.g., typographically (distinct from the typographical description
